This data set is from the Federal Reserve of St.Louis (Fred). It is the average fixed rate mortgage in the United States over the last 30 years. The data is provided by Freddie Mac who obtains it from applications submitted to Freddie Mac from lenders across the country. Its index is monthly and the keys are the date and mortgage rate. I am adding the CPI data to use two and three month lag cpi as predictor variables

I chose this dataset because I am interested in forecasting this as it seems to be increasing and would like to see if I can make a solid forecast model that will accurately forecast the future and I have interest in the real estate market as well. One of my roommates is making an algorithm that looks at Zillow and is focused in and around our hometown of Loveland Ohio and I figured this would be a good project to go with it.

This can hopefully help potential homebuyers decide if it is the right time for them to purchase a house. For some of my roommates we are interested in investing in real estate (once we arent poor) and enjoy learning about the market as well. I predict mortgage rates will raise in the future and hopefully this will predict the same. Assuming there is a recession now and potentially a depression in the future, that would be the best time start buying property and capitalize off it. Being able to predict Interest rates would help us make better decisions when it comes to buying real estate especially since the real estate industry is so diluted with so many people wanting to be real estate agents, flip homes, rent out homes, etc, having key data to help make better decisions could be factor in being successful.

Dataset_tsb <- Dataset %>%
  mutate(Week_number = row_number(),
          fixed_rate =MORTGAGE30US,
         CPI = CPALTT01USM659N,
         Three_month_lag_CPI = lag(CPI, n = 12L),
         Two_month_lag_CPI = lag(CPI, n = 8L),
        one_year_lag_fixed_rate = lag(fixed_rate, n=52L)) %>%
  as_tsibble(index = Week_number, regular = TRUE) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(Three_month_lag_CPI), !is.na(one_year_lag_fixed_rate), !is.na(Two_month_lag_CPI)) %>% 
  select(-MORTGAGE30US,
         -CPALTT01USM659N)

I added Month columns to both he CPI dataset and fixed mortgage dataset so i could merge them without having to separate date tables as fixed mortgage was weekly statistics and CPI was monthly.

I made the row_number of the data into the week_number and used it as the index as I struggled to find an alternate way to be able to covert the data to a tsibble.

I changed the names to make the CPI and fixed rate columns on the dataset more identifiable by mutating them and giving them a new name and deleting the old names.

I added Two_month_lag_CPI, Three_month_lag_CPI, and one_year_fixed_rate_lag to use as predictor variables and see fi there was any correlation or trend between them and fixed rate.

I used !is.na to take out any missing data.

It looks like it has cycle pattern of going up and down over the years but seems relatively random with when and how long the cycles last.

From 1971 to the early 80s the fixed mortgage rate is increasing rapidly.

From mid 1980s it is on a relative downward trend until around mid to late 2020.

The anomaly of the fixed mortgage rate increasing rapidly from 1971 to the early 80s is most likely do to the instability in the economy at the time as there was a recession in the US from November 1973-March of 1975 as well as January 1980-July 1980 and July 1981-November 1982.

From 1971 to early 1980s there is a upward trend in fixed mortgage rate, from early to mid 1980s to 2020 there is a gradual trend downward.

There does seem to cycles of the rate moving up or down over periods of time which is to be expected.

It seems after the pandemic started in 2020 the downward trend switched to an upward trend.

We will use the two month , three month lag of CPI, and one year lag of the fixed rate as predictors since there is levels of correlation in all.

The data looks autocorrelated from a ACF test

From Kpss test it shows the dataset is not stationary.

The dataset does not need not need a seasonal difference.

The dataset does need a difference.

The dataset is stationary after taking a difference of fixed rate.

Dataset_tsb_updated <- Dataset_tsb %>%
  mutate(diff_fixed_rate = difference(fixed_rate), lag_diff_fixed_rate = lag(diff_fixed_rate)) %>% 
           filter(!is.na(diff_fixed_rate), !is.na(lag_diff_fixed_rate))

train <- Dataset_tsb_updated %>% filter(year(Month) < 2018)
test <- Dataset_tsb_updated %>% filter(year(Month) >= 2018)

I chose to split at 2018 because I believe it gives the training set a lot of previous data to use and still offers sufficient data from 2018 onwards to test against.

FitTSLModels <- train %>% model( lm1 = TSLM(diff_fixed_rate ~ Two_month_lag_CPI),
                           lm2 = TSLM(diff_fixed_rate ~ Three_month_lag_CPI),

                           lm4 = TSLM(diff_fixed_rate ~ Two_month_lag_CPI +Three_month_lag_CPI + one_year_lag_fixed_rate))

I chose RMSE statistic because I want the dataset to be more sensitive to big outliers and be able to account for large outleirs in the future. I chose TSLM because it had the lowest RMSE and also had the lowest MAEand MASE statistics. It also seemed to do a better job of predicting the test data from an eye test when forecasted out. Plus it had three predictor variables that all had levels of correlation to the fixed mortgage rate and difference of fixed mortgage rate. I was never able to get NNETAR to run so I commented it out. Feel free to try to run it and see if it is better.

Model_Picked <- Dataset_tsb_updated %>%
 model(TSLMBEST = TSLM(diff_fixed_rate ~ Two_month_lag_CPI +Three_month_lag_CPI + one_year_lag_fixed_rate)
  )


diff_fixed_rate.lm = lm(diff_fixed_rate ~ Two_month_lag_CPI +Three_month_lag_CPI + one_year_lag_fixed_rate, data=Dataset_tsb_updated)#using this equation to find the  the coefficents


future_scenarios <- scenarios(
  Increase = new_data(Dataset_tsb_updated, 156) %>%
    mutate(Two_month_lag_CPI =.1, Three_month_lag_CPI=.06, one_year_lag_fixed_rate=0.03),
  Decrease = new_data(Dataset_tsb_updated, 156) %>%
    mutate(Two_month_lag_CPI=-.11, Three_month_lag_CPI=-0.06, one_year_lag_fixed_rate=-.03),
  names_to = "Scenario")




fcast <- forecast(Model_Picked, new_data = future_scenarios)

Dataset_tsb_updated %>%
  autoplot(diff_fixed_rate) +
  autolayer(fcast) +
  labs(title = "Difference of US Fixed Mortgage Rate Increase", y = "% change")

I forecasted 3 years into the future and that was to give it a long enough time to implement the future scenarios.

Some things to watch out for is if there a depression soon, it will most likely have an effect on fixed mortgage rates as well as if inflation keeps increasing as well. If the economy recovers quickly the fixed mortgage rates will probably decrease as well.
